title: For Sale/Trade:  Rare Marlin 39D .22 levergun
postcontent:
Marlin did some funny things in the 1970s, this rifle is an example. Based on the iconic 39A, this 20" round barreled rifle was made from 1971-1973. This version with the white buttstock and pistol grip spacers was made in 71 and early 72. fewer than 16,000 were made. To add to the weirdness, the serial number on this rifle indicates it was made in 1970; before this model existed. My 39D is nearly perfect. I know it has been shot only because after I got it, I took it out and put a box of 50 through it. It is a fantastic little rifle. That said, I believe it belongs with someone else. Guns For Sale - Colt Model 1908 .380 ACP -- Semi-Auto Pistol Mf'd 1933 - C&R OK

LSB#: 130125FM01

Make: Colt

Model: Model 1908

Serial Number: 112171

Year of Manufacture: 1933

Caliber: .380 ACP

Action Type: Single Action Semi-Auto Pistol with Detachable Magazine

Markings: The right side of the slide is marked "Colt Automatic / Calibre .380 Hammerless". The left side of the slide is marked "Colt's PT. F.A. Mfg. Co Hartford, CT. U.S.A. / Patented Apr. 20. 1897. Dec. 22. 1903" followed by the Rampant Horse logo. The left side of frame is marked "112171" with an "I" and a “VP” on the left trigger guard bow. The right side of the trigger guard is marked "75".

Barrel Length: About 3/4"

Sights / Optics: The front sight is a fixed blade. The rear sight is a dovetail set notch.

Stock Configuration & Condition: The grips are "Sile" made and checkered wood. The grips closely resemble the original Colt panels. The checkering has worn and the panels have darkened a bit from age and handling. There are no splits or cracks. The grips rate in about Good overall condition.

Type of Finish: Nickel

Finish Originality: Reapplied

Bore Condition: The bore is a bit fouled, but otherwise almost bright and the rifling is only lightly worn. There is only very mild erosion in the bore.

Overall Condition: This handgun retains about 95% of its reapplied metal finish. There is some flaking in the serrations and general surface dulling and frosting. The metal was very smooth and apparently free of erosion before the refinish. The safety notch on the slide is battered a bit. Most of the wear described is to the surface/finish and does not penetrate into the metal. The screw heads are only a bit worn. The markings are clear, and but for the Rampant Colt logo would almost look to have not been refinished at all. Overall, this handgun rates in about Very Good condition.

Mechanics: The action functions correctly. We did not fire this handgun.

Box, Paperwork & Accessories: One blued reproduction magazine is included. Also included is a soft and pliable black clip holster. The holster has been modified at the heel for this pistol, but is otherwise in Very Good condition and is great for this gun.

Our Assessment: John Browning designed it and Colt built it – what more needs to be said. The early Colt automatics are in our opinion the best series of firearms ever produced, and from a partnership like Colt & Browning they better be. Everyone has come to appreciate these guns, carrying them even today, as they are one of the few compact automatics with a slide lock. This pistol shows a lot of finish and is in the ever loved .380 ACP.

title: For Sale:  Heckler & Koch HK41 .308 w/HK Accessories
postcontent: Scarce, highly collectable Heckler & Koch HK41 .308 caliber semi-auto rifle. Very few imported into the United States; all were imported in 1966 by the Santa Fe Division of the Golden State Arms Corp. It is estimated that fewer than 400 rifle were produced and only a portion of these were imported to the U.S. The first generation HK41 has the G3 style "paddle" magazine release (in addition to the standard side release), and also features the lower push pin hole that was originally inteded for attachment of the selective fire G3 trigger group. There featuresmade it too easy to illegally convert the rifle to full auto and were deleted in the later production HK41 and HK91 rifles. First generation HK41 rifle were "grandfathered" by the ATF, and are legal to own in their orginal configuaration. Condition: NRA Excellant. All numbers match, bright bore. Very minor handling marks, scratches. Original HK Accessories: Nine Magazines, Bi-Pod, Bayonet w/sheath and case, Two Slings-1 leather/1 Cotton, Sight Tool, Small Parts Kit, Extra Flash Hider, Magazine Loader, Original Owners Manual, Assorted HK Literature
